  "sourceNotes": "Flourless almond cakes appear widely in Mediterranean and Sephardic Jewish cookbooks, particularly for Passover, where leavened flour is avoided. Eliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845), Project Gutenberg, includes almond meal preparations. The Italian version (torta di mandorle) appears in nineteenth-century Italian household texts. The form here follows the classic pattern of ground almonds, sugar, eggs, and butter.",
